## 5. Market Analysis

- **Industry size and trends:** US dumpster rental is a multi-billion-dollar market tied to construction and renovation activity. Roll-off / temporary-container demand tracks construction starts, remodeling, and disaster/clean-up cycles. The Tahoe Basin specifically sees steady remodel and rebuild activity (high-value second homes, defensible-space and wildfire-driven work) supporting durable demand.
- **Growth drivers and barriers:** Drivers — construction and renovation activity, wildfire mitigation and clean-up work, tourism-driven commercial turnover. Barriers / headwinds — construction cyclicality, seasonality (Tahoe winters compress the building season), landfill tipping fees and disposal-cost inflation, and truck/container capex.
- **Regulatory note:** Subscription residential trash collection in the Tahoe region is franchised (e.g., South Tahoe Refuse in South Lake Tahoe; Tahoe Truckee Sierra Disposal in Truckee, franchise through ~2028). **Temporary roll-off / construction-debris containers are generally outside those exclusive residential franchises**, which is why an independent roll-off operator can exist in this market — but the broker should confirm there is no local permitting or franchise constraint on roll-off service.
- **Competitive landscape (peer benchmarks):**
  - **South Tahoe Refuse & Recycling (STR)** — incumbent franchised hauler, South Lake Tahoe; broad residential/commercial collection plus roll-off.
  - **Tahoe Truckee Sierra Disposal (TTSD)** — franchised hauler for Truckee/North Tahoe; competes for roll-off and C&D work.
  - **National roll-off marketplaces / brokers** (Hometown, ASAP, etc.) — aggregators that resell capacity; not asset operators but they pressure pricing.
  - Typical disclosed roll-off-business sale multiples run ~3–5x EBITDA for sub-$1M-EBITDA operators; larger platforms command 4–6x+.

